eland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1216–1292":"1216–1292","1219–1298":"1219–1298","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1242–1322":"1242–1322","1260–1322":"1260–1322","1198–Male":"1198–Deceased","1194–Female":"1194–Deceased","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1194":"1194","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1322":"1322","1298":"1298","before 1240":"before 1240","1219":"1219","Wingfield, Suffolk, England":"Wingfield, Suffolk, England","Dennington, Suffolk, England":"Dennington, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Lethringham, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Letheringham, Suffolk, England":"Letheringham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wingfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Winfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Winfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from Wingfield in Derbyshire, Bedfordshire, Suffolk, and Wiltshire. The Derbyshire placename probably derives from Old English <i>winn</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’. The Bedfordshire placename may derive from Old English <i>wince</i> ‘nook, corner’ + <i>feld</i>. The Suffolk placename may derive from the Old English personal name <i>Wiga</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) or Old English <i>wīg</i> ‘idol’ + <i>feld</i>. The Wiltshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wina</i> + Old English <i>feld</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":8,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":43,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":74,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Wingfield was born in 1216, in Suffolk, England, his father, John de Wingfield, was 18 and his mother, Mrs. John de Wingfield, was 23. He married Joan Fastolf before 1240, in Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1292, in his hometown, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1216–1292":"1216–1292","1219–1298":"1219–1298","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1242–1322":"1242–1322","1260–1322":"1260–1322","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1194–Female":"1194–Surnud","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1194":"1194